 {"id":"frankenredis-txo","title":"Fix RESP parser read_line off-by-one at MAX_LINE_LENGTH boundary","description":"## Problem\n\nfr-protocol/src/lib.rs line 260: The read_line loop condition \\\"while i + 1 < max_search\\\" means the last position checked for \\\\r is max_search-2. If \\\\r falls at exactly max_search-1 (offset start + MAX_LINE_LENGTH - 1) with \\\\n at max_search, the valid \\\\r\\\\n pair is missed and the line is incorrectly rejected as LineTooLong.\n\n## Impact\n\nLow — this only affects RESP lines whose content (excluding \\\\r\\\\n) is exactly MAX_LINE_LENGTH-1 bytes long (64 KiB - 1). This is a rare edge case but violates the principle that any valid RESP frame should parse correctly.\n\n## Fix\n\nChange the loop condition from \\\"i + 1 < max_search\\\" to \\\"i + 1 <= max_search\\\" (or equivalently, \\\"i < max_search\\\"). Ensure the i+1 bounds check for \\\\n doesn't read past input.len().\n\n## Files to Modify\n\n- crates/fr-protocol/src/lib.rs: read_line loop condition","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-03-25T03:11:03.775225391Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-25T03:34:51.062354543Z","closed_at":"2026-03-25T03:34:51.061004207Z","close_reason":"Fixed read_line loop to check full MAX_LINE_LENGTH range before declaring LineTooLong","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
